@PlatinumAltaria "obfuscate what fascism is so people don't realise they're living in it." - Whatever society you're alluding to, and whatever fascism is.

For what it's worth, I don't have a clear definition of fascism - it applies to the regimes of Mussolini and Hitler, but I'm not sure to what else. Maybe Eco's concept of ur-fascism is the best way of analyzing things, or maybe that's an intellectually lazy excuse to label "fascist" a broader category or rightwing authoritarianism to which the label doesn't apply, some of which might predate even Mussolini's socialist phase.

And sure, there are similarities and differences between fascist Italy and the US. One is the role of ruling parties. In Italy, the party was in charge, and maintained its power by partnering with business. In the US, the major parties are very much servants to business interests - Sheldon Wolin's term "inverted totalitarianism" is a ridiculously hyperbolic way of characterizing the US system, but points at one key difference between fascism and the dominant modern form of capitalism.

